heading_context: Support your child or partner's student finance application
chunks.html_content:
You may be asked for information about your household income if your child or partner has applied for student finance in England.

Your information will be used to work out if your child or partner can get extra money on top of the Tuition Fee Loan and the basic Maintenance Loan.

If you do not share information about your household income, your child or partner will only get the minimum amount of student finance.

heading_context: Support your child or partner's student finance application
Create an account or sign in
chunks.html_content:
After your child or partner applies, you’ll get an email from Student Finance England (SFE) within 24 hours.

You’ll need to wait for the email before you create a student finance account or sign in. You cannot use the same account as your child or partner.

heading_context: Support your child or partner's student finance application
Create an account or sign in
chunks.html_content: If you’ve had student finance or supported an application before, you’ll need to sign in to your student finance account. You can reset your login details if you’ve forgotten them.

Support your child or partner's student finance application

If you’ve had student finance or supported an application before, you’ll need to sign in to your student finance account. You can reset your login details if you’ve forgotten them.

heading_context: Support your child or partner's student finance application
What information you’ll need
chunks.html_content:
You’ll be asked for your National Insurance number once you’ve signed in. SFE will use this to get information about your income from the previous tax year from HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC).

You’ll also need to say if you have:

  • paid into private pensions 
  • made additional voluntary contributions
  • children (other than the student) who depend on you financially

If you do not have a National Insurance number, you’ll need to complete a form and provide evidence to show how much you earned.

heading_context: Support your child or partner's student finance application
What happens next
chunks.html_content:
SFE will write to your child or partner when all your information has been confirmed. They cannot share details of the loan with you without your child or partner’s consent.

If your information is still being processed when your child or partner starts their course, they’ll still get the Tuition Fee Loan and the basic Maintenance Loan (if they’re eligible).

heading_context: Support your child or partner's student finance application
Supporting a continuing student
If you gave income details for the current tax year
chunks.html_content:
Your child or partner needs to apply for student finance each year.

When they apply, you’ll get an email within 24 hours. The email will have a link to sign in to your account, where you must give:

  • your marital status
  • any changes to the information you provided the previous year
  • details of any private pensions, additional voluntary contributions and other child dependants

You can use the same income details that you provided last year.

If your income has dropped by at least 15% again, you can send in a new current tax year income assessment form.

heading_context: Support your child or partner's student finance application
Check you’re eligible for a current year income assessment
If your income was £25,000 or less
chunks.html_content:
You will qualify for a current year income assessment for the 2023 to 2024 academic year if your expected household income is both:

  • at least 15% lower for the full current tax year compared to the year you gave details for

  • £58,291 or less for the full current tax year

The current tax year is 6 April 2023 to 5 April 2024.

You will have given details for 6 April 2021 to 5 April 2022.

The student must be on a course where their student finance is based on your household income.

If your household income is £58,291 or more a year but less than £70,040 a year, you may still qualify depending on the student’s circumstances. Check how you’re assessed and paid.

If your income was £25,000 or less for the year you gave details for, the student may be receiving the full amount they’re entitled to. You might still be able to apply for an assessment if the student needs it to get:

  • a bursary or scholarship from a university or college

  • extra student finance for children or dependent adults

heading_context: Support your child or partner's student finance application
How to apply for the 2023 to 2024 academic year
chunks.html_content:
To apply, you must have already created an online account and given information about a previous tax year.

You then need to complete these 3 steps.

  1. Fill in a current year income assessment form and send it to Student Finance England.

  2. Keep your income details up to date during the year.

  3. Confirm your actual income at the end of the tax year.

chunks.html_content: You cannot apply until the tax year you’re applying for has started.

heading_context: Support your child or partner's student finance application
Fill in a current year income assessment form
chunks.html_content:
Fill in the current tax year income assessment form for 2023 to 2024 and send it to Student Finance England. You can send it through your online account, or print out the form and send it by post.

If you’re the parent of the student and your partner also lives in the household, you’ll both need to complete the form, even if only one income has changed.

This is because you’re assessed on household income from the same tax year.

When you’re estimating your income, include:

  • working overtime or extra hours
  • any maternity or paternity pay
  • any casual work, shift work or contract work
  • any pay rises, bonuses or redundancy pay
  • income changes from changing jobs or returning to work
  • income from self-employment

heading_context: Support your child or partner's student finance application
Keep your income details up to date
chunks.html_content:
If your income changes during the year, fill in a new current tax year income assessment form for 2023 to 2024. Then send it to Student Finance England as soon as possible.

You’ll be reassessed and the amount of money your student is entitled to might go up or down. Student Finance England will contact the student directly to let them know.

heading_context: Support your child or partner's student finance application
Confirm your income at the end of the tax year
If you’re self-employed
chunks.html_content:
After the tax year finishes you must send evidence of what your actual income was for the year. You’ll usually be sent a form to fill in at the start of May.

If you have not completed your tax return yet, fill in the form to ask to delay providing evidence until after the Self Assessment deadline (January the following year).

You still need to return evidence for any other employment, for example if you had a salaried job earlier in the year.

heading_context: Support your child or partner's student finance application
Confirm your income at the end of the tax year
If your household income is different from what you estimated
chunks.html_content:
How much your student is entitled to will change. If your actual income was:

  • lower - your student might be entitled to more money
  • higher - your student will have to repay any extra money they received
